\begin_layout Standard
We selected pollen samples to calibrate against AGWB estimates from forest
 survey data using an approach similar to that of Dawson et al (2016) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "dawson2016quantifying"

\end_inset

.
 Calibration samples from the settlement-era pollen data were all determined
 by expert elicitation to be contemporaneous with the settlement era based
 on historical forest survey data.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A panel of experts in Midwestern paleoecology
\end_layout

\end_inset

 were presented with unlabeled depth series of taxonomic percentages from
 every site with sufficient data spanning the settlement era and were asked
 to identify the depth of the "settlement horizon" using their own criteria
 and to report their certainty in that decision.
 Sites were excluded from the calibration dataset if no expert could identify
 a settlement horizon sample or if experts disagreed about the location
 of the settlement horizon sample within plus or minus two samples.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This process resulted in a set of 232 sites, comprising the sites identified
 in Dawson et al (2016) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "dawson2016quantifying"

\end_inset

 and additional sites from cores added to the Neotoma database since 2016
 (Fig.
 S
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Sampling-points-for"

\end_inset

).
 These sites are distributed evenly across geographic space, climate, and
 AGWB at the settlement era (Fig.
 S
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:pls-point-biomass"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before conducting exploratory analyses and initial model fitting, we removed
 a random selection of one-third of the sites (n
\begin_inset Formula $_{1/3}$
\end_inset

= 78) as a held-out test set on which to evaluate the final model, discussed
 further in following sections.
 We used the remaining two-thirds of the sites as our calibration training
