\begin_layout Subsection
Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our modeling framework contains two distinct parts.
 We begin with a calibration model to estimate the nonlinear multivariate
 relationship between pollen proportions and AGWB.
 The basic assumption of this model is that species composition (and therefore
 pollen composition) is related to AGWB.
 We assess this by plotting the species AGWB composition for different total
 AGWB bins on the settlement landscape (Fig.
 S
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tiles"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement p
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/araiho/ReFAB/final_figures/[5-A]settlement.biomass.tiles.pdf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/araiho/ReFAB/final_figures/[5-B]settlement.pollen.tiles.pdf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(left) The shading in each box represents the proportion of total AGWB that
 each species contributes in each AGWB category from the PLS AGWB estimates.
 (right) The shading in each box represents the proportion of pollen from
 each tree species averaged over the sites falling in each AGWB category
 (as determined from the PLS estimates).
 This illustrates that AGWB is associated with the relative composition
 of pollen of the various taxa.
 However, the taxon-level relationships to biomass will vary between the
 PLS and pollen data, because of intertaxonomic differences in pollen productivi
ty and dispersal that will cause different degrees of over- and under-representa
tion among plant taxa in the pollen record.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:tiles"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

The calibration model estimates coefficients of spline basis functions that
 nonlinearly relate pollen-taxa vectors to AGWB point estimates.
 Once calibrated, we fit a prediction model that uses the coefficients estimated
 in the calibration model, pollen-count data available at multiple times,
 and a model structure that ensures that AGWB varies smoothly over time,
 to make AGWB point predictions at individual sites.
 This prediction model is used to make predictions every 100 years from
 the time of settlement (100 years before present) to 10,000 years before
 present.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use a modern statistical technique known as inverse modeling that models
 pollen counts as a function of AGWB rather than a regression modeling approach
 that models AGWB as a function of pollen counts (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "blarquez2015tree,seppa2009calibrated"

\end_inset

 for examples of the regression approach).
 The inverse modeling approach allows us to build a statistical model for
 changes in AGWB over time that enforces smoothness in the AGWB process
 through a prior distribution on AGWB as a latent (i.e., unobserved) temporal
 process.
 This allows us to combine information from the pollen data while enforcing
 realistic changes over time.
 In contrast, a regression modeling approach would not be able to enforce
 smoothness over time; jumps in pollen composition would translate directly
 into (unrealistic) jumps in AGWB.
 A full mathematical description of the smoothing function is described
 in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Biomass-temporal-process"

\end_inset

.
 Also note that we do not explicitly model pollen dispersal, which allows
 us to avoid having to specify a statistical model for the unknown species
 composition across the landscape.
 These choices allow us to keep the model relatively simple and relate directly
 the univariate variable of interest (total AGWB) to the multivariate dependent
 variable (pollen composition).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our two-step approach also allows us to have greater flexibility in model
 development and assessment.
 Alternatively, we could have fit the calibration and prediction models
 in a comprehensive framework, but we separate them to be able to develop
 alternative calibration models and fit prediction models one site at a
 time.
 Neither model includes spatial uncertainty, which preserves model simplicity
 and computational efficiency, leaving spatio-temporal modeling of all the
 sites jointly for future work.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "dawson2016quantifying"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "paciorek2009mapping"

\end_inset

 for similar strategies.
\end_layout

