\begin_layout Subsubsection
AGWB temporal process
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Biomass-temporal-process"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
AGWB evolution is generally a smooth, long-term process at centennial scales
 across a landscape composed of multiple forest stands (i.e., at the scale
 sensed by most fossil pollen records collected from lakes and mires).
 However, under some circumstances rapid changes in AGWB can occur within
 days (e.g., catastrophic wildfire), years (e.g., drought-related tree mortality)
 or decades (e.g., mid-Holocene hemlock decline, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "davis1998patchy,booth2012multi"

\end_inset

).
 Thus we want a statistical model for the evolution of AGWB that generally
 enforces smoothness but also allows for rapid change at some times.
 Our temporal model for the evolution of AGWB uses a generalized Pareto
 (GP) distribution to provide nonstationary temporal structure (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "armagan2013generalized"

\end_inset

, eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:smoothing"

\end_inset

).
 A GP distribution has a spike at zero (like a Laplace distribution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kotz2012laplace"

\end_inset

 or spike-and-slab model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ishwaran2005spike"

\end_inset

) combined with a heavy tail that allows for outlying values.
 Such distributions have been used for model selection 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "taddy2013multinomial,armagan2013generalized"

\end_inset

 as well as representing random processes, which is known as trend filtering
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "tansey2017multiscale,ramdas2016fast,roualdes2015bayesian"

\end_inset

.
 Here we embed the GP distribution in a third-order random-walk process
 model to induce smoothness as well as nonstationarity (eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:smoothing"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also considered first-order 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t}\sim\mathrm{GP}\left(b_{t-1},\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 and second-order 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t}\sim\mathrm{GP}\left(2b_{t-1}-b_{t-2},\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 models.
 The first-order model allows for sharp jumps but does not impose smoothness.
 The AGWB estimates and uncertainty are not smooth and are very sensitive
 to small changes in pollen proportions, yet we expect AGWB to generally
 vary smoothly in time with few landscape-scale abrupt changes for any given
 century.
 We also found that a simple random walk model did not fit well to sites
 where the likelihood was bimodal.
 Second-order models were more smooth but still showed evidence of insufficient
 smoothness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also used a prior constraint that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t}\in[0,b_{max}],\,t=1,\ldots,T$
\end_inset

, imposed during the MCMC sampling.
 We selected the upper limit on AGWB based on the maximum point estimates
 of AGWB in our calibration dataset where 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{max}=294$
\end_inset

 based on the maximum AGWB in the PLS in our calibration dataset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the MCMC, we sample 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,2,...,100$
\end_inset

 to estimate the temporal evolution of AGWB over the time period of interest.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Process variance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimate a fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 common to all sites (eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:smoothing"

\end_inset

).
 Estimating a single value across all sites is useful because there is limited
 information to estimate this parameter on a site-specific basis, and because
 we expect that the process of AGWB evolution has similar behavior across
 sites.
 It also avoids difficulties with achieving good MCMC performance for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 We chose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=0.03$
\end_inset

 through a simple cross-validation exercise similar to those described in
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Calibration-model-selection"

\end_inset

.
 To choose this fixed value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, we assessed the log likelihoods across a grid of values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 from 0 to 1.
