 AGWB at each of the 77 reconstruction sites.
 Using these pairs, we calculated all differences between pollen proportions
 and AGWB for each taxa or taxa grouping at each site.
 This resulted in large taxon specific matrices of pollen proportion differences
 and corresponding AGWB differences.
 We aggregated these difference pairs across the three site clusters discussed
 in the previous section.
 Then, we estimated taxon- and cluster-specific coefficients between these
 differences using a robust regression from the 'MASS' package 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ripley2013package"

\end_inset

.
 These coefficients represented the relationship between changing pollen
 proportion to changing AGWB (i.e.
 sensitivity) for each taxa across the three clusters.
 For many pollen taxa, there were small differences in pollen proportion
 corresponding to larger differences in AGWB.
 This occurred because a particular pollen taxa may be changing and therefore
 influencing AGWB when another pollen taxa is not changing.
 This phenomenon resulted in a large mass of paired differences where change
 in pollen proportion equaled zero.
 These points initially affected our estimates of AGWB sensitivity to pollen
 proportion change.
 To reduce the influence of these points, we removed all points where the
 pollen proportion difference was between -0.03 and 0.03.
 We also removed pollen proportion points that were beyond five standard
 deviations away from the pollen proportion differences by cluster and taxon
 to remove the effects of strong outliers.
 We provide some examples of this analysis in Fig.
 S 
