 The effects of hemlock decline on regional vegetation composition are well
 known and are easily visible in our pollen prediction dataset (Fig.
 S 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:hemlock-decline"

\end_inset

 top).
 However, the effects on AGWB are mixed: signals are apparent at individual
 sites but not across the entire domain or within the individual clusters
 (Fig.
 4D, main text).
 In our sensitivity analysis described in the previous section, we found
 that hemlock population change was directly positively related to AGWB
 change more than the majority of taxonomic groupings (Fig.
 3D, main text), so we expected to see a regional AGWB signal from hemlock
 population decline.
 We performed a separate investigation to determine the effects of hemlock
 population decline on AGWB magnitude at the site-level.
 By looking at reconstructions at individual sites with high proportions
 of hemlock, we found evidence for the effects of hemlock population decline
 on site-level AGWB (Fig.
 S
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:hemlock-decline"

\end_inset

 bottom), where average hemlock pollen proportion and AGWB magnitude decreased
 at sites with relatively higher hemlock percentages between 6,000-5,000
 YBP versus 4,500-3,500 YBP (mean hemlock proportion = 0.058 versus 0.024,
 mean AGWB estimate = 122.88 Mg/ha versus 118.88 Mg/ha).
 We also found that these declines in AGWB were not directly overlapping
 in time.
 A simple linear model with log AGWB estimate as the response variable and
 hemlock proportion, longitude, and hemlock and longitude interaction as
 scaled independent variables showed that the interaction between hemlock
 proportion and longitude significantly affected the AGWB estimate (p-value
 = .000125, coefficient estimate = -0.06).
 Previous studies have shown that hemlock decline may have been caused by
 an abrupt climate shift, disease, or coupled climate change and disease
 introduction.
 Furthermore, the effects of climate and/or disease on hemlock populations
 were not necessarily synchronous in time and varied spatially 
